Definition 4.18. Let $X$ be a small site, and $\mathbf{K}$ be a locally finitely presentable category. For a presheaf $\mathcal{A}$, define a presheaf $\left(\mathcal{A}\right)_{\mathbf{K}}^{+}$ (or simply $\mathcal{A}^{+})$ by the following: $\mathcal{A}^{+}\left(U\right)=\underset{R}{\underrightarrow{\lim}}~{}\underset% {\left(V\rightarrow U\right)\in\mathbf{C}_{R}}{\underleftarrow{\lim}}~{}% \mathcal{A}\left(V\right)=\underset{R}{\underrightarrow{\lim}}~{}Hom_{\mathbf{% Set}^{\left(\mathbf{C}_{X}\right)^{op}}}\left(R,\mathcal{A}\right)$ where $R\subseteq h^{U}$ runs over all covering sieves over $U$.
Definition 1.17. A category $\mathbf{I}$ is called filtered if $\mathbf{I}$ is $\aleph_{0}$-filtered. A category $\mathbf{I}$ is called cofiltered if $\mathbf{I}^{op}$ is filtered. A diagram $\mathcal{D}:\mathbf{I\rightarrow K}$ is called (co)filtered if $\mathbf{I}$ is a (co)filtered category.
Definition 5.15. Let $G\in\mathbf{K}$. We denote by the same letter $G$ the following constant precosheaf on $X$ with values in $\mathbf{K}$ or $\mathbf{Pro}\left(\mathbf{K}\right)$: $G\left(U\right){:=}G$ for all open subsets $U$.
Definition 1.22. Let $X$ be a topological space. A morphism $X\rightarrow\left(Y_{j}\right)_{j\in\mathbf{I}}$ in $\mathbf{Pro}\left(H\left(\mathbf{Top}\right)\right)$ is called an $H\left(\mathbf{Top}\right)$-expansion (or simply expansion) if for any polyhedron $P$ the following mapping $\underrightarrow{\lim}_{j}\left[Y_{j},P\right]=\underrightarrow{\lim}{}_{j}Hom% _{H\left(\mathbf{Top}\right)}\left(Y_{j},P\right)\longrightarrow Hom_{H\left(% \mathbf{Top}\right)}\left(X,P\right)=\left[X,P\right]$ is bijective where $\left[Z,P\right]$ is the set of homotopy classes of continuous mappings from $Z$ to $P$. An expansion is called polyhedral (or an $H\left(\mathbf{Pol}\right)$-expansion) if all $Y_{j}$ are polyhedra.
Definition 3.6. Let $\mathbf{K}$ be a complete and cocomplete category, let $\mathbf{C}$ be a small category, and let $\mathcal{A}:\mathbf{C}\longrightarrow\mathbf{K,~{}}\mathcal{B}:\mathbf{C}% \longrightarrow\mathbf{Set,~{}}\mathcal{F}:\mathbf{C}^{op}\longrightarrow% \mathbf{Set,}$ be functors. Then define the following objects: (1) $Hom_{\mathbf{Set}^{\mathbf{C}}}\left(\mathcal{B},\mathcal{A}\right)\in\mathbf{K}$ is the end [ML98, Chapter IX.5], of the bifunctor $\left(U,V\right)\mapsto Hom_{\mathbf{Set}}\left(\mathcal{B}\left(U\right),% \mathcal{A}\left(V\right)\right)$, i.e. $Hom_{\mathbf{Set}^{\mathbf{C}}}\left(\mathcal{B},\mathcal{A}\right){:=}\ker% \left(\mathop{\displaystyle\prod}\limits_{U}Hom_{\mathbf{Set}}\left(\mathcal{B% }\left(U\right),\mathcal{A}\left(U\right)\right)\rightrightarrows\mathop{% \displaystyle\prod}\limits_{U\rightarrow V}Hom_{\mathbf{Set}}\left(\mathcal{B}% \left(U\right),\mathcal{A}\left(V\right)\right)\right).$ (2) $\mathcal{A\otimes}_{\mathbf{Set}^{\mathbf{C}}}\mathcal{F=F\otimes}_{\mathbf{% Set}^{\mathbf{C}^{op}}}\mathcal{A}\in\mathbf{K}$ is the coend [ML98, Chapter IX.6], of the bifunctor $\left(U,V\right)\mapsto\mathcal{A}\left(U\right)\otimes_{\mathbf{Set}}\mathcal% {F}\left(V\right)$, i.e. $\mathcal{A\otimes}_{\mathbf{Set}^{\mathbf{C}}}\mathcal{F}{:=}coker\left(% \mathop{\displaystyle\coprod}\limits_{U\rightarrow V}\mathcal{A}\left(U\right)% \otimes_{\mathbf{Set}}\mathcal{F}\left(V\right)\rightrightarrows\mathop{% \displaystyle\prod}\limits_{U}\mathcal{A}\left(U\right)\otimes_{\mathbf{Set}}% \mathcal{F}\left(U\right)\right).$
Definition 1.7. A subcategory $\mathbf{C\subseteq D}$ is called reflective (respectively coreflective) iff the inclusion $\mathbf{C\hookrightarrow D}$ is a right (respectively left) adjoint. The left (respectively right) adjoint $\mathbf{D\rightarrow C}$ is called a reflection (respectively coreflection).
Definition 4.25. Let $\mathbf{K}$ admit filtered colimits, and let $f:\mathcal{A\rightarrow B}$ be a morphism in the category of presheaves $\mathbf{pS}\left(X,\mathbf{K}\right)$. We say that $f$ is a local isomorphism iff $f_{x}:\mathcal{A}_{x}\rightarrow\mathcal{B}_{x}$ is an isomorphism for any $x\in X$. In a situation when $\mathbf{K}\subseteq\mathbf{L}$, and $\mathcal{A},\mathcal{B}\in\mathbf{pS}\left(X,\mathbf{K}\right)\subseteq\mathbf% {pS}\left(X,\mathbf{L}\right),$ we will say that $f$ is $\mathbf{K}$-local (respectively $\mathbf{L}$-local) isomorphism iff $\left(f\right)_{x}^{\mathbf{K}}:\left(\mathcal{A}\right)_{x}^{\mathbf{K}}% \longrightarrow\left(\mathcal{B}\right)_{x}^{\mathbf{K}}$ (respectively $\left(f\right)_{x}^{\mathbf{L}}:\left(\mathcal{A}\right)_{x}^{\mathbf{L}}% \longrightarrow\left(\mathcal{B}\right)_{x}^{\mathbf{L}}$) is an isomorphism for any $x\in X$.
Definition 2.4. A precosheaf $\mathcal{A}$ is called smooth ([Bre97, Corollary VI.3.2 and Definition VI.3.4], or [Bre68, Corollary 3.5 and Definition 3.7]), iff there exist precosheaves $\mathcal{B}$ and $\mathcal{B}^{\prime}$, a cosheaf $\mathcal{C}$, and strong local isomorphisms $\mathcal{A}\rightarrow\mathcal{B}\leftarrow\mathcal{C}$, or, equivalently, strong local isomorphisms $\mathcal{A}\leftarrow\mathcal{B}^{\prime}\rightarrow\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 1.11. Let $\mathcal{F}\in\mathbf{Set}^{\mathbf{C}^{op}}$. The comma category $\mathbf{C}_{\mathcal{F}}$ is defined as follows: $\displaystyle Ob\left(\mathbf{C}_{\mathcal{F}}\right){:=}\left\{\left(V,\alpha% \right)~{}|~{}V\in\mathbf{C},\alpha\in\mathcal{F}\left(V\right)\right\},$ $\displaystyle Hom_{\mathbf{C}_{U}}\left(\left(V_{1},\alpha_{1}\right),\left(V_% {2},\alpha_{2}\right)\right){:=}\left\{\beta:V_{1}\rightarrow V_{2}~{}|~{}% \mathcal{F}\left(\beta\right)\left(\alpha_{2}\right)=\alpha_{1}\right\}.$
Definition 1.2. A diagram in $\mathbf{C}$ is a functor $\mathcal{D}:\mathbf{I}\longrightarrow\mathbf{C}$ where $\mathbf{I}$ is a small category. A cone (respectively cocone) of the diagram $\mathcal{D}$ is a pair $\left(U,\varphi\right)$ where $U\in\mathbf{C}$, and $\varphi$ is a morphism of functors $\varphi:U^{const}\rightarrow\mathcal{D}$ (respectively $\mathcal{D}\rightarrow U^{const}$). Here $U^{const}$ is the constant functor: $\displaystyle U^{const}\left(i\right)$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle U,i\in\mathbf{I},$ $\displaystyle U^{const}\left(i\rightarrow j\right)$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle\mathbf{1}_{U}.$
Definition 3.1. ([4, 1.5]) A set $\mathcal{D}$ of parametrizations of $X$ is a diffeology of $X$ if the following axiom are satisfied. (i) The set $\mathcal{D}$ contains all constant parametrizations. (ii) Let $p:U\to X$ be a parametrization. If for every point $r$ of $U$, there exists an open neighborhood $V$ of $r$ such that $p|_{V}$ belongs to $\mathcal{D}$, then $p$ is in $\mathcal{D}$. (iii) For every element $p:U\to X$ of $\mathcal{D}$ and for every smooth map $f:V\to U$ for $V\subset\mathbb{R}^{q}$, the composite $p\circ f$ is in $\mathcal{D}$.
Definition 4.2. Let $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$ be a strict ringed space. We call $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$ strongly fine if for any open set $U$ of $X$, $U$ admits a partition of unity in ${\mathcal{O}_{X}}|_{U}(U)$ the ring of global sections of the induced sheaf $(U,{\mathcal{O}_{X}}|_{U})$.
Definition 5.1. Let $(S,{\mathcal{C}}(S))$ be a stratifold and $(E,{\mathcal{C}}(E))$ a differential space. A morphism of diferrential spaces $\pi:(E,{\mathcal{C}}(E))\rightarrow(S,{\mathcal{C}}(S))$ is a vector bundle over $(S,{\mathcal{C}}(S))$ if the following conditions are satisfied. (1) $E_{x}:=\pi^{-1}(x)$ is a vector space over ${\mathbb{R}}$ for $x\in S$. (2) There exist an open covering $\{U_{\alpha}\}_{\alpha\in J}$ of $S$ and an isomorphism $\phi_{\alpha}:\pi^{-1}(U_{\alpha})\rightarrow U_{\alpha}\times{\mathbb{R}}^{n_% {\alpha}}$ of differential spaces for each $\alpha\in J$. Here $\pi^{-1}(U_{\alpha})$ is regards as a subdifferential space of $(E,{\mathcal{C}}(E))$; see Remark 2.3, and $U_{\alpha}\times{\mathbb{R}}^{n_{\alpha}}$ is considered the product of the substratifold $(U_{\alpha},{\mathcal{C}}(U_{\alpha}))$ of $(S,{\mathcal{C}}(S))$ and the manifold $({\mathbb{R}}^{n_{\alpha}},C^{\infty}({\mathbb{R}}^{n_{\alpha}}))$; see Section 6. (3) The diagram $\xymatrix@C30pt@R15pt{\pi^{-1}(U_{\alpha})\ar[rr]^{\phi_{\alpha}}\ar[rd]_{\pi}% &&U_{\alpha}\times{\mathbb{R}}^{n_{\alpha}}\ar[ld]^{pr_{1}}\\ &U_{\alpha}&}$ is commutative, where $pr_{1}$ is the projection into the first factor. (4) The composite $pr_{2}\circ\phi_{\alpha}|_{E_{x}}:E_{x}\rightarrow U_{\alpha}\times{\mathbb{R}% }^{n_{\alpha}}\rightarrow{\mathbb{R}}^{n_{\alpha}}$ is a linear isomorphism, where $pr_{2}:U_{\alpha}\times{\mathbb{R}}^{n_{\alpha}}\rightarrow{\mathbb{R}}^{n_{% \alpha}}$ denotes the projection into the second factor.
Definition 2.1. Let $S$ be a topological space and ${\mathcal{C}}$ an $\mathbb{R}$-subalgebra of $C^{0}(S)$ the $\mathbb{R}$-algebra of real-valued functions. A pair $(S,{\mathcal{C}})$ is a differential space if the following conditions are satisfied. (i) ${\mathcal{C}}$ is locally detectable; that is, $f\in{\mathcal{C}}$ if and only if for any $x\in S$, there exist an open neighborhood $U$ of $x$ and an element $g\in{\mathcal{C}}$ such that $f|_{U}=g|_{U}$. (ii) For any $f_{1},...,f_{k}$ in ${\mathcal{C}}$ and smooth function $g:\mathbb{R}^{k}\to\mathbb{R}$, the function $h:S\to\mathbb{R}$ defined by $h(x)=g(f_{1}(x),....,f_{k}(x))$ is in ${\mathcal{C}}$.
Definition 5.2. Let $\pi:(E,{\mathcal{C}}(E))\to(S,{\mathcal{C}}(S))$ be a vector bundle over a stratifold $(S,{\mathcal{C}}(S))$. Let ${\mathcal{O}}_{S}$ be the structure sheaf of $S$ and $U$ an open set of $S$. A morphism of differential spaces $s:(U,{\mathcal{O}}_{S}(U))\rightarrow(E,{\mathcal{C}}(E))$ is called a section on $U$ if $\pi\circ s=id_{(U,{\mathcal{O}}_{S}(U))}$. We denote by $\Gamma(U,E)$ the set of all sections.
Definition 3.5. Let $(S,{\mathcal{C}})$ and $(S^{\prime},{\mathcal{C}}^{\prime})$ be stratifolds. A map $f:S\to S^{\prime}$ in $\mathsf{Top}$, namely a continuous map, is admissible if for any $x\in S$, there exist local retractions $r_{x}$ and $r_{f(x)}$ near $x$ and $f(x)$, respectively such that $r_{f(x)}fr_{x}=r_{f(x)}f$.
Definition 3.2. Let $(X,\mathcal{D}_{X})$ and $(Y,\mathcal{D}_{Y})$ be diffeological spaces. A map $f:X\to Y$ is a morphism of diffeological spaces, denoted $f:(X,\mathcal{D}_{X})\to(Y,\mathcal{D}_{Y})$, if for any element $p\in\mathcal{D}_{X}$, the composite $f\circ p$ is in $\mathcal{D}_{Y}$.
Definition 2.2. Let $S$ be a locally compact, Hausdorff space with countable basis. A differential space $(S,{\mathcal{C}})$ is a $k$-dimensional stratifold if the following four conditions are satisfied. (1) For any $i$, the subspace $S^{i}:=\{x\in S\mid\text{dim }\!T_{x}S=i\}$ is a manifold, possible empty. Moreover, for each $x\in S^{i}$, the restriction gives rise to an isomorphism $i^{*}:{\mathcal{C}}_{x}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\cong}}{{\to}}C^{\infty}(S^{i})_% {x}.$ (2) The skeleta $\Sigma^{r}:=\bigcup_{i\leq r}S^{i}$ are closed in $S$. (3) $\text{dim }\!T_{x}S\leq k$ for all $x\in S$. (4) For each $x\in S$ and open neighborhood $U$ of $x$ in $S$, there exists a nonnegative function $\rho\in{\mathcal{C}}$ such that $\rho(x)\neq 0$ and $\text{supp }\!\rho:=\overline{\{p\in S\mid\rho(p)\neq 0\}}\subset U$. We call such a function a bump function at $x$ on $U$.
Definition 3.2. A open cover $U_{i}$ of $X$ is good if any finite intersection $U_{i_{0}\ldots i_{k}}$ is contractible.
Definition A.2. Let $X$ be a paracompact space. A sheaf $\mathcal{F}$ of groups over $X$ is fine if for every two disjoint closed subsets $A,B\subset X,A\cap B=\emptyset$, there is an endomorphism of the sheaf of groups $\mathcal{F}\rightarrow\mathcal{F}$ which restricts to the identity in a neighborhood of $A$ and to the $0$ endomorphism in a neighborhood of $B$.
Definition 2.2. [Shift] Let $\mathcal{E}=(E^{\bullet}_{i},a)$ be a twisted perfect complex. We define its shift $\mathcal{E}[1]$ to be $\mathcal{E}[1]=(E[1]^{\bullet}_{i},a[1])$ where $E[1]^{\bullet}_{i}=E^{\bullet+1}_{i}\text{ and }a[1]^{k,1-k}=(-1)^{k-1}a^{k,1-% k}.$ Moreover, let $\phi:\mathcal{E}\to\mathcal{F}$ be a morphism. We define its shift $\phi[1]$ as $\phi[1]^{p,q}=(-1)^{q}\phi^{p,q}.$
Definition 2.4. A locally ringed space $(U,\mathcal{O}_{U})$ is called p-good if it satisfies the following two conditions 1. For every perfect complex $\mathcal{P}^{\bullet}$ on $U$, there exists a strictly perfect complex $\mathcal{E}^{\bullet}$ on $U$ together with a quasi-isomorphism $u:\mathcal{E}^{\bullet}\overset{\sim}{\to}\mathcal{P}^{\bullet}$. 2. The higher cohomologies of any sheaf vanish, i.e. $H^{k}(U,\mathcal{F})=0$ for any sheaf $\mathcal{F}$ on $U$ and any $k\geq 1$. An open cover $\{U_{i}\}$ of $X$ is called a p-good cover if $(U_{I},\mathcal{O}_{X}|_{U_{I}})$ is a p-good space for any finite intersection $U_{I}$ of the open cover.
Definition 3.4. Let $P_{i},\leavevmode\nobreak\ Q_{i}$ be sheaves of $\mathcal{A}$-modules on $U_{i}$. A descent of $P_{i}$ to $X$ modulo $Q_{i}$ consists of a sheaf of $\mathcal{A}$-modules $R$ on $X$ together with the following data • a collection of $\mathcal{A}$-module maps $\tau_{i}:Q_{i}\rightarrow P_{i};$ • a collection of $\mathcal{A}$-module maps $\psi_{i}:R|_{U_{i}}\rightarrow P_{i}$ • a collection of $\mathcal{A}$-module maps $\xi_{ji}:R|_{U_{ji}}\rightarrow Q_{j}|_{U_{ji}};$ which satisfy the following conditions 1. On $U_{ji}$ the maps $\psi_{i}$ and $\psi_{j}$ are compatible with the transition function $\theta_{ji}$ modulo $Q_{i}$, i.e. $\psi_{j}-\theta_{ji}\psi_{i}=\tau_{j}\xi_{ji}$ 2. Each of the $\psi_{i}$ is surjective modulo $Q_{i}$ in the following sense: For any point $x\in U_{i}$ and $u_{i}$ in the fiber $P_{i}|_{x}$, there exist an $v\in R|_{x}$ and a $w_{i}\in Q_{i}|_{x}$, such that $u_{i}=\psi_{i}(v)-\tau_{i}(w_{i}).$
Definition 2.3. [Mapping cone] Let $\phi^{\bullet,-\bullet}$ be a closed degree zero map between twisted perfect complexes $\mathcal{E}=(E^{\bullet},a^{\bullet,1-\bullet})$ and $\mathcal{F}=(F^{\bullet},b^{\bullet,1-\bullet})$ , we can define the mapping cone $\mathcal{G}=(G,c)$ of $\phi$ as follows (see [OTT85] Section 1.1): $G^{n}_{i}:=E^{n+1}_{i}\oplus F^{n}_{i}$ and $c^{k,1-k}_{i_{0}\ldots i_{k}}=\begin{pmatrix}(-1)^{k-1}a^{k,1-k}_{i_{0}\ldots i% _{k}}&0\\ (-1)^{k}\phi^{k,-k}_{i_{0}\ldots i_{k}}&b^{k,1-k}_{i_{0}\ldots i_{k}}\end{% pmatrix}.$
Definition 3.3. Let $P_{i},\leavevmode\nobreak\ Q_{i}$ be sheaves of $\mathcal{A}$-modules on $U_{i}$. A descent data of $P_{i}$ modulo $Q_{i}$ consists of the following data • a collection of $\mathcal{A}$-module maps $\tau_{i}:Q_{i}\rightarrow P_{i};$ • a collection of $\mathcal{A}$-module maps $\theta_{ji}:P_{i}|_{U_{ji}}\rightarrow P_{j}|_{U_{ji}};$ • a collection of $\mathcal{A}$-module maps $\vartheta_{kji}:P_{i}|_{U_{kji}}\rightarrow Q_{k}|_{U_{kji}};$ which satisfy the following conditions 1. $\theta_{ji}$ is a cocycle module $Q_{i}$, more precisely $\theta_{ki}-\theta_{kj}\theta_{ji}=\tau_{k}\vartheta_{kji};$ 2. $\theta_{ii}=id_{P_{i}}$.
Definition 2.1. Let $(X,\mathcal{A})$ be a ringed paracompact topological space and $\mathcal{U}=\{U_{i}\}$ be an locally finite open cover of $X$. A twisted perfect complex consists of locally free graded sheaves $E^{\bullet}_{i}$ of $\mathcal{A}$-modules together with a collection of morphisms $a=\sum_{k\geq 0}a^{k,1-k}$ where $a^{k,1-k}\in C^{k}(\mathcal{U},\text{Hom}^{1-k}(E,E))$ and which satisfies the equation $\delta a+a\cdot a=0.$ More explicitly, for $k\geq 0$ $\delta a^{k-1,2-k}+\sum_{i=0}^{k}a^{i,1-i}\cdot a^{k-i,1-k+i}=0.$ The twisted perfect complexes on $(X,\mathcal{A},\{U_{i}\})$ form a dg-category: the objects are the twisted perfect complexes $(E^{\bullet}_{i},a)$ and the morphism from $\mathcal{E}=(E^{\bullet}_{i},a)$ to $\mathcal{F}=(F^{\bullet}_{i},b)$ are $C^{\bullet}(\mathcal{U},\text{Hom}^{\bullet}(E,F))$ with the total degree. Moreover, the differential on a morphism $\phi$ is given by $d\phi=\delta\phi+b\cdot\phi-(-1)^{|\phi|}\phi\cdot a.$ We denote the dg-category of twisted complexes on $(X,\mathcal{A},\{U_{i}\})$ by $\text{Tw}_{\text{perf}}(X,\mathcal{A},U_{i})$. If there is no danger of confusion we can simply denote it by $\text{Tw}_{\text{perf}}(X)$.
Definition 3.1 ([Wei16] Definition 3.11). Let $(S^{\bullet},d)$ be a complex of $\mathcal{A}(X)$-modules. We define its associated twisted perfect complex, $\mathcal{T}(S)$, by restricting to the $U_{i}$’s. In more details let $(E^{\bullet},a)=\mathcal{T}(S)$ then $E^{n}_{i}=S^{n}|_{U_{i}}$ and $a^{0,1}_{i}=d|_{U_{i}},\leavevmode\nobreak\ a^{1,0}_{ij}=id\text{ and }a^{k,1-% k}=0\text{ for }k\geq 2.$ The $\mathcal{T}$ of morphisms is defined in a similar way. We call the dg-functor $\mathcal{T}:\mathfrak{L}(X,\mathcal{A})\to\text{Tw}_{\text{perf}}(X,\mathcal{A% },U_{i})$ the twisting functor.
Definition A.1. A sheaf $\mathcal{F}$ on a topological space $X$ is called soft if any section over any closed subset of $X$ can be extended to a global section. In other words, for any closed subset $K\subset X$, the restriction map $\mathcal{F}(X)\rightarrow\mathcal{F}(K)$ is surjective.
Definition 3.1. Let $S$ be a Boolean inverse monoid. A Boolean inverse monoid representation of $S$ in a unital C*-algebra $A$ is a map $\pi:S\to A$ such that 1. $\pi(0)=0$, 2. $\pi(st)=\pi(s)\pi(t)$ for all $s,t\in S$, and 3. $\pi(s\vee t)=\pi(s)+\pi(t)-\pi(ss^{*}t)$ for all compatible $s,t,\in S$.
Definition 2.2. A Boolean inverse monoid is a distributive inverse monoid $S$ with the property that $E(S)$ is a Boolean algebra, that is, for every $e\in E(S)$ there exists $e^{\perp}\in E(S)$ such that $ee^{\perp}=0$, $e\vee e^{\perp}=1$, and the operations $\vee,\wedge,\perp$ satisfy the laws of a Boolean algebra [GH09, Chapter 2].
Definition 3.6. Let $S$ be an inverse semigroup, let $s\in S$ and $e\leqslant s^{*}s$. Then we say that 1. $e$ is fixed by $s$ if $se=e$, and 2. $e$ is weakly fixed by $s$ if for all $0\neq f\leqslant e$, $fsfs^{*}\neq 0$. Denote by $\mathcal{J}_{s}:=\{e\in E(S)\mid se=e\}$ the set of all fixed idempotents for $s\in S$. We note that an inverse semigroup for which $\mathcal{J}_{s}=\{0\}$ for all $s\notin E(S)$ is called E*-unitary.
Definition 4.4. Let $A$ be a C*-algebra. A bounded linear functional $\tau:A\to\mathbb{C}$ is called a trace if 1. $\tau(a^{*}a)\geq 0$ for all $a\in A$, 2. $\tau(ab)=\tau(ba)$ for all $a,b\in A$. A trace $\tau$ is said to be faithful if $\tau(a^{*}a)>0$ for all $a\neq 0$. A trace $\tau$ on a unital C*-algebra is called a tracial state if $\tau(1)=1$. The set of all tracial states of a C*-algebra $A$ is denoted $T(A)$.
Definition 2.1. An inverse semigroup $S$ is called distributive if whenever we have a compatible set $F\subset_{\text{fin}}S$, then $\bigvee_{s\in F}s$ exists in $S$, and for all $t\in S$ we have $t\left(\bigvee_{s\in F}s\right)=\bigvee_{s\in F}ts\hskip 28.452756pt\text{and}% \hskip 28.452756pt\left(\bigvee_{s\in F}s\right)t=\bigvee_{s\in F}st.$
Definition 4.1. Let $S$ be a Boolean inverse monoid. A function $\mu:E(S)\to[0,\infty)$ will be called an invariant mean if 1. $\mu(s^{*}s)=\mu(ss^{*})$ for all $s\in S$ 2. $\mu(e\vee f)=\mu(e)+\mu(f)$ for all $e,f\in E(S)$ with $ef=0$. If in addition $\mu(1)=1$, we call $\mu$ a normalized invariant mean. An invariant mean $\mu$ will be called faithful if $\mu(e)=0$ implies $e=0$. We will denote by $M(S)$ the affine space of all normalized invariant means on $S$.
Definition 3.2. Let $S$ be a Boolean inverse monoid. Then the universal C*-algebra of $S$, denoted $C^{*}(S)$, is defined to be the universal unital C*-algebra generated by one element for each element of $S$ subject to the relations which say that the standard map of $S$ into $C^{*}(S)$ is a Boolean inverse monoid representation. The map $\pi_{u}$ which takes an element $s$ to its corresponding element in $C^{*}(S)$ will be called the universal Boolean inverse monoid representation of $S$, and we will sometimes use the notation $\delta_{s}:=\pi_{u}(s)$.
Definition 4.8. Let $\mathcal{G}$ be an étale groupoid. A regular Borel probability measure $\nu$ on $\mathcal{G}^{(0)}$ is called $\mathcal{G}$-invariant if for every bisection $U$ one has that $\nu(r(U))=\nu(d(U))$. The affine space of all regular $\mathcal{G}$-invariant Borel probability measures is denoted $IM(\mathcal{G})$.
Definition 5.2. Let $\mathcal{O}$ be an ordered set. A subgroup $\mathcal{A}\subseteq{\rm OP}(\mathcal{O})$ is completely integrally closed for every $a,a^{\prime}\in\mathcal{A}$, $a^{n}\leq a^{\prime}$ for all $n\in\mathbb{N}$ implies $a\leq{\rm id}_{\mathcal{P}}$.
Definition 2.6. Let $\mathcal{O}$ and $\mathcal{P}$ be ordered sets. The set of order preserving functions from $\mathcal{O}$ to $\mathcal{P}$ is ${\rm OP}(\mathcal{O},\mathcal{P})=\{f:|\mathcal{O}|\to|\mathcal{P}|\,|\,f(x)% \leq f(y)\text{ if }x\leq y\}\,.$ We view ${\rm OP}(\mathcal{O},\mathcal{P})$ as an ordered set such that $f\leq g$ if and only if $f(x)\leq g(x)$ for all $x\in\mathcal{O}$. We use the shorthand notation ${\rm OP}(\mathcal{O})={\rm OP}(\mathcal{O},\mathcal{O})$. We also say that $f\in{\rm OP}(\mathcal{O},\mathcal{P})$ is an embedding if for any $x,y\in\mathcal{O}$, $f(x)\leq f(y)$ implies $x\leq y$. An isomorphism is a surjective embedding. Given an ordered set $\mathcal{O}$, we denote by ${\rm Aut}(\mathcal{O})$ the group of all isomorphisms in ${\rm OP}(\mathcal{O})$.
Definition 3.1. Let $\mathcal{O},\mathcal{P}$ be ordered sets. We say that $\psi\in{\rm PD}(\mathcal{O},\mathcal{P})$ is extremal if there exist ${\rm lex}_{\psi},{\rm uex}_{\psi}\in{\rm OP}(\mathcal{O},\mathcal{P})$ such that ${\rm OP}_{\psi}(\mathcal{O},\mathcal{P})=[{\rm lex}_{\psi},{\rm uex}_{\psi}]\,.$ If this is the case, we call ${\rm lex}_{\psi}$ (resp. ${\rm uex}_{\psi}$) the lower extension (resp. the upper extension) of $\psi$. We denote by ${\rm E}(\mathcal{O},\mathcal{P})$ the set of all extremal elements of ${\rm PD}(\mathcal{O},\mathcal{P})$.
Definition 7.1. A filter basis on an ordered set $\mathcal{O}$ is a collection $F$ of nonempty subsets of $\mathcal{O}$ that is closed under finite intersections. To each filter basis $F$ of $\mathcal{O}$ we associate the partially defined function $\psi_{F}\in{\rm PD}({\rm OP}(\mathcal{O},\mathbb{R}),\widehat{\mathbb{R}})$ such that ${\rm dom}(\psi_{F})=\bigcup_{\mathcal{S}\in F}{\rm dom}(\psi_{\mathcal{S}})\,,$ where $\psi_{\mathcal{S}}$ is defined as in Example 4.7 and $\psi_{F}(f)=\psi_{\mathcal{S}}(f)$ for each $f\in{\rm dom}(\psi_{\mathcal{S}})$ and for each $\mathcal{S}\in F$.
Definition 2.8. Let $\mathcal{O}$ and $\mathcal{P}$ be ordered sets. The set of partially defined functions from $\mathcal{O}$ to $\mathcal{P}$ is ${\rm PD}(\mathcal{O},\mathcal{P})=\bigcup_{\mathcal{S}}{\rm OP}(\mathcal{S},% \mathcal{P})$ where $\mathcal{S}$ ranges over all subsets of $\mathcal{O}$. We also write ${\rm PD}(\mathcal{O})$ for ${\rm PD}(\mathcal{O},\mathcal{O})$. If $\psi\in{\rm PD}(\mathcal{O},\mathcal{P})$ we denote its domain by ${\rm dom}(\psi)$ and its image by ${\rm im}(\psi)$. The set of extensions of $\psi$ is the subset ${\rm OP}_{\psi}(\mathcal{O},\mathcal{P})\subseteq{\rm OP}(\mathcal{O},\mathcal% {P})$ consisting of all functions whose restriction to ${\rm dom}(\psi)$ coincides with $\psi$.
Definition 3.4. Given $\psi\in{\rm PD}(\mathcal{O},\mathcal{P})$, the subset of $\psi$-bounded elements of $\mathcal{O}$ is the union ${\rm B}(\psi)$ of all elements in ${\rm Int}(\mathcal{O};{\rm dom}(\psi))$. We say that $\psi$ is encompassing if $\mathcal{O}={\rm B}(\psi)$. Moreover, for each $\psi\in{\rm E}(\mathcal{O},\mathcal{P})$ we define the bounded Darboux set of $\psi$ to be ${\rm BDar}(\psi)={\rm Dar}(\psi)\cap{\rm B}(\psi)\,.$
Definition 2.1. A (partially) ordered set is a set $\mathcal{O}$ together with a reflexive, antisymmetric, and transitive relation which we denote by $\leq$.
Definition 4.1. An ordered set $\mathcal{P}$ is complete if ${\rm PD}(\widehat{\mathcal{P}})={\rm E}(\widehat{\mathcal{P}},\widehat{P})$.
Definition 7.2. Let $\mathcal{O}$ be an unordered set and let $F$ be a filter basis on $\mathcal{O}$. A function $f\in{\rm OP}(\mathcal{O},\mathbb{R})$ is $F$-convergent if there exists $\lim_{F}(f)\in\widehat{\mathbb{R}}$ such that for every $\varepsilon>0$ there exists $\mathcal{S}\in F$ such that $f(x)\in[\lim_{F}(f)-\varepsilon,\lim_{F}(f)+\varepsilon]$ for all $x\in\mathcal{S}$.
Definition 2.10. Let $\mathcal{O},\mathcal{P}$ be ordered sets. A subset $\Psi\subseteq{\rm PD}(\mathcal{O},\mathcal{P})$ is extendable if for any $\psi_{1},\psi_{2}\in{\rm PD}(\mathcal{O},\mathcal{P})$, the restrictions of $\psi_{1}$ and $\psi_{2}$ to ${\rm dom}(\psi_{1})\cap{\rm dom}(\psi_{2})$ coincide. If $\Psi$ is extendable, we define its common extension to be $\psi\in{\rm PD}(\mathcal{O},\mathcal{P})$ such that ${\rm dom}(\psi)=\bigcup_{\psi^{\prime}\in\Psi}{\rm dom}(\psi^{\prime})$ and $\psi(x)=\psi^{\prime}(x)$ for every $x\in{\rm dom}(\psi^{\prime})$ and for every $\psi^{\prime}\in\Psi$.
Definition 2.7. If $\mathcal{O}$ is an ordered set, we define its augmentation to be the ordered set $\widehat{\mathcal{O}}$ such that 1) $|\widehat{\mathcal{O}}|=|\mathcal{O}|\cup\{-\infty,+\infty\}$; 2) the canonical inclusion of $|\mathcal{O}|$ into $|\widehat{\mathcal{O}}|$ defines an embedding of $\mathcal{O}$ into $\widehat{\mathcal{O}}$; 3) $\widehat{\mathcal{O}}=[-\infty,+\infty]$.
Definition 6.3. We denote by ${\rm Dar}(\mathcal{O})$ the Darboux set of ${\rm id}_{{\rm im}(Y)}$ and refer to ${\rm Dar}^{\prime}(\mathcal{O})={\rm Dar}(\mathcal{O})\setminus\{\pm\infty\}$ as the Darboux completion of $\mathcal{O}$. We also denote by ${\rm BDar}(\mathcal{O})$ the bounded Darboux set of ${\rm id}_{{\rm im}(Y)}$.
Definition 3.3. For each $\psi\in{\rm E}(\mathcal{O},\mathcal{P})$, we define the Darboux set of $\psi$ to be ${\rm Dar}(\psi)=\{x\in\mathcal{O}\,|\,{\rm lex}_{\psi}(x)={\rm uex}_{\psi}(x)\}$ and denote by ${\rm ex}_{\psi}\in{\rm PD}(\mathcal{O},\mathcal{P})$ the Darboux extension of $\psi$ i.e. restriction of ${\rm uex}_{\psi}$ (or equivalently of ${\rm lex}_{\psi}$) to ${\rm Dar}(\psi)$.
Definition 3.2. An $X$-scheme $\pi:Y\to X$ is called a Nisnevich neighborhood of $Z$ in $X$ if the morphism $\pi$ is etale and the fiber product $Z\times_{X}Y$ is isomorphic to $Z.$
